english:
  title: A Petition to Exempt Gold and Silver Tribute
  author: Byeon Gyeryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly reflect that Heaven's love for mankind and a father's love for his children represent the pinnacle of compassion. Thus, when people face the Heaven or when children face their fathers, should they encounter desperate circumstances and bitter suffering, it is the natural order of the world that they cry out urgently for salvation. I respectfully consider that Your Majesty extends the protection of Heaven and the care of a father across all lands within and beyond the four seas, allowing all creatures to fulfill their nature and enabling every common man and woman to exhaust their effort. Yet if your servant, facing an unavoidable situation, merely harbors worry and melancholy without bringing the matter before you, then your servant would not be regarding Your Majesty with the hopes placed in Heaven and parents. Therefore, your servant ventures to present this matter, humbly beseeching Your Majesty's consideration.

    Your servant reflects that our small realm possesses barren lands with scanty resources. That we produce neither gold nor silver is known throughout the world. Therefore, when the Great Founder Emperor, in the tenth month of the fifth year of Hongwu, issued his sacred decree through the Central Secretariat, it stated: "From ancient times, tributary states and distant kingdoms present only tokens of allegiance and sincerity. Henceforth, let the tribute consist solely of local products—cloth and silk, no more than three to five bolts as a gesture of respect. All else shall cease." By the seventh year of Hongwu, at the new year audience, only cloth was accepted, while all gold, silver, and vessels were returned. This was because the Great Founder, with far-reaching wisdom, clearly understood that our small state produces no gold or silver—a principle consonant with the ancient sage Yu who assessed tribute according to local resources. Is this not what the ancients meant when they said that wise rulers of different ages follow the same path?

    Yet at that time, foreign merchants from the Yuan Dynasty had brought some gold and silver, which we still possessed. Our state continued to present tribute as before. Thus have fifty years elapsed. Our resources have been exhausted, our public treasuries depleted. We have resorted to levies upon every household. Yet in the homes of our officials and common people alike, there remains not a single vessel of gold or silver. Pressed by such dire circumstances, your servant cannot remain silent and ventures to lay bare his heart, risking offense to the Celestial Authority.

    Furthermore, your servant reflects upon his lineage. His ancestor, the late King of Kangheun, received special favor from the Great Founder, was granted royal rank, and bestowed a kingdom's name. Your servant's father, the late King of Gongjeong, and your servant himself have each received imperial commendation. For three generations spanning nearly forty years, we have enjoyed such continuous grace and gifts that scarcely a year has passed without imperial bounty—so much that it cannot be enumerated. Comparing with history, no small state has received such profound imperial benevolence as ours today. Your servant has never forgotten, not even for a moment, his desire to repay this grace if even remotely possible. How then could he dare to claim absence what exists, abandon customary tribute, and deceive the Celestial Hearing?

    Your servant's words spring from deepest sincerity. Heaven above, the Celestial Emperor, mountains and rivers, spirits and gods—all oversee from above and witness from beside. How could your servant dare to deceive? How could he dare?

    Your servant humbly begs that Your Majesty forgive his verbose utterance, take pity on his urgent circumstances, look to the sacred precedent of the sage-king Yu, and follow the great teachings of the Founder Emperor. Embodying Heaven and Earth's love for all people and extending a parent's protective care for children, may Your Majesty graciously issue a decree exempting our tribute of gold and silver, allowing us instead to present the products of our land. Then not only would your servant and all the people of this realm rejoice in the radiance of Your Majesty's virtue, but the spirits of your servant's forefathers would also be moved with gratitude in the unseen realm, and your servant's descendants would be blessed with deep benevolence and abundant grace for ten thousand generations without end. Your servant humbly begs Your Majesty to extend a measure of this compassion.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Great Founder Emperor (太祖高皇帝) refers to the Hongwu Emperor, founder of the Ming Dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Yu the Great and 'assessing tribute according to local resources' (任土作貢) refers to the ancient Chinese principle of allowing tributary states to present tributes based on what their land naturally produces.
  - key: ''
    value: Byeon Gyeryang was a Korean envoy who submitted this memorial seeking exemption from gold and silver tribute to the Ming court, based on the argument that Joseon's geography made such tribute economically unsustainable.
